You're looking to track transformations which is done mathematically with an affine transformation matrix. 1. Assign four x,y vertices to the untransformed rect. 2. Use matrix math to calc the transformed (eg rotated) vertices. 3. Draw the transformed rect. 4. To "hit-test" the rectangle, you invert the matrix to get the untransformed x,y marquee vertices. 5. Hit-test the untransformed marquee vs the original untransformed rect. Info about transformation matrices is readily available on SO & elsewhere

@awinston: It is not completely a coincidence; the numbers representable in any floating-point  format using a base of 2 are all integer multiples of powers of 2 (including 2 to negative integer powers). So any power of two within range is representable in such a floating-point format. Since the maximum value representable in some binary integer is one less than some power of two, it is at most one away from a value representable in a `double`. (It can be closer if the numbers representable in a double are close together at that point.)
